===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|toft(e)|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|tofe, toffe|lang=frm}} 'tuft', from [[Late Latin]] (near Vegezio) {{term|tufa}} 'helmet crest', from Germanic (compare {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|ðūf|lang=ang}} 'tuft', {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|þúfa|lang=non}} 'mound', {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|tuva|lang=sv}} 'tussock, grassy hillock'), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*þūbǭ}}, {{m|gem-pro|*þūbaz}}; akin to Latin ''tūber'' 'hump, swelling', Ancient Greek ''typhē'' 'cattail (used to stuff beds)'.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[bunch]] of [[feather]]s, [[grass]] or [[hair]], etc., held together at the [[base]].
# A [[cluster]] of [[thread]]s drawn tightly through [[upholstery]], a [[mattress]] or a [[quilt]], etc., to [[secure]] and [[strengthen]] the [[padding]].
# A small [[clump]] of [[tree]]s or [[bush]]es.
# {{context|historical|lang=en}} A gold [[tassel]] on the cap worn by [[titled]] [[undergraduate]]s at English universities.
# {{context|historical|lang=en}} A person [[entitle]]d to wear such a tassel.
#* T. Hughes
#*: Several young '''tufts''', and others of the faster men.

